714329f-a.text:
180 East 91st Street, south side, between Park and Lexington Avenues.
About 1911.
Neg #1325

714330f.text:
71st Street, south side, east from and including Park uvenue. The buildings in the foreground are a part of the Presbyterian Hospital. The hosptal has already moved uptown to the new Medical Centre at Broadway and 168th Street, and the buildings shown here will be demolished wthin the next few months.
March 31, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.

714331f-a.text:
71st Street, north side, east from Park Avenue. The dark building in the centre is the former nurses home of Presbyterian Hospital. Above is St. James Protestant Episcopal Church.
March 31, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.

714333f-a.text:
71st Street, west of, adjoining,and at the N.W. corner of Park Avenue, seen across the clearing after the demolition of Presbyterian Hospital. The building in the centre was formerly the nurses' home of the hospital. At the right one of the hospital buildings may be seen in the last stage of demolition.
June 8, 1928
P.L. Sperr

722332f-a.text:
Park Avenue, at S. E. corner of 71st Street, showing newly built private residence.
About 1912.

722333f-a.text:
748 Park Avenue at N.W. corner of 71st Street, built about 1906. This building, together with the double house 750-52 and the Presbyterian Nurses' Home, seen to the left on 71st Street, will be replaced in 1929 by a 17-story apartment building.
About 1912.
The Pictorial News Co., Photographer.
gift of E. M. Jenks.
Neg #823

722334f.text:
752 and 754 Park Avenue, west side, between 71st and 72nd Streets, showing part of the corner house, 78 West 72nd Street. At right, No. 752 will be demolished in 1929. It is the northern half of a double house (see picture of N.W. corner of 71st Street).
About 1912.
